\f0\b0  ordinance, it may not be enacted soon enough for the Smiths and for Ted Wheeler of Wheeler Farms, who hired the Smiths to put up the turbine.\
Mary Smith said Wheeler could lose $80,000 in grants and incentives if the turbine isn't running by midsummer, and the turbine might have to be sold.\
"And we may lose other Ada County customers who want to install small wind turbines," she said.\
The Smiths operate Treasure Valley Wind & Solar. They contacted Ada County in October about getting a permit and were told they could not get one because no ordinance allowed it. Then they called the governor's office and the 
\f1\b Idaho
\f0\b0  Office of 
\f1\b Energy
\f0\b0  Resources, which suggested the Smiths explore obtaining a conditional-use permit.\
But the county does not allow conditional use permits for wind turbines outside the Rural Preservation District. A wind project developer in the Rural Preservation District must submit conditional-use permit and master site plan applications, Ada County spokeswoman Jessica Donald said. The Wheeler site, off Eagle Road south of Columbia Road, is outside the district.\
"You can go anywhere outside Ada County and you have no problem putting up a wind turbine," Mary Smith said. "I don't see the reason why the permit can't be given, at least a conditional-use, until they get an ordinance together, especially since they know we have financial deadlines."\
An Ada County ordinance allows wind turbines, considered power plants, only in the Rural Preservation District that lies mainly in outlying and peripheral areas but some areas in the foothills just north of Boise, Donald said.\
A goal of the Rural Preservation District is to protect agricultural, rangeland and wildlife areas from adjacent development while permitting public gathering facilities like schools and churches, she said. Limiting development of hazardous areas and directing development toward urban and planned-community areas are among other goals.\
